  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The article \"Measured measurement,\" authored by Markus Aspelmeyer and published in *Nature Physics* in 2009, has garnered 11 citations, indicating a measurable academic uptake in the fields of quantum physics and measurement theory. The work has been referenced in various scholarly discussions, showcasing its relevance in contemporary research, particularly within quantum tomography.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Measured measurement\" significantly contributes to the discourse on quantum measurement and tomography. Since its publication, the article has found its place in the academic canon, with a citation count of 11, reflecting its influence on subsequent research in quantum mechanics. Notably, the citations span across multiple years, indicating sustained relevance and engagement with the core concepts introduced by Aspelmeyer.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The article's impact is further demonstrated through its inclusion in diverse scholarly venues, such as *Optics Communications* and *Chinese Physics B*, among others. This intertextuality underscores its interdisciplinary appeal and adaptability across various fields linked to quantum physics. The diverse citation landscape illustrates how concepts from the article have been vital for advancing discussions on quantum state transformations and statistical mechanics.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In addition to academic citations, the work has sparked discussions within the scientific community, evidenced by a mention on the platform Bluesky. This active engagement indicates that the article continues to resonate with contemporary discourse, inviting both critique and expansion of its themes. Furthermore, the article has been utilized as a teaching resource, with links appearing in educational videos, highlighting its role in informing new generations of researchers in quantum physics.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, \"Measured measurement\" not only enhances our understanding of quantum mechanics but also exemplifies how pivotal research can cross disciplinary boundaries, fostering dialogue and inquiry in various domains related to physics and measurement. Its legacy continues as it influences both current research and educational pathways in the field.</p>",
